    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial and operational disclosures, here are the details regarding the AI segment\'s operating losses, cost breakdown, and the specific compute and infrastructure costs associated with Grok.\n\n### 1. AI Segment Operating Loss Details\nThe AI segment has incurred significant operating losses since inception, with the company projecting a multi-year investment horizon before achieving sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA. \n\n**Loss from Operations:**\n*   **Q1 2026 (Three months ended March 31, 2026):** Increased by $1,533 million to **$(2,469) million** (compared to $(936) million in Q1 2025). This was primarily driven by higher cloud computing, GPU depreciation, data center infrastructure, and employee expenses.\n*   **FY 2025:** Increased by $4,794 million to **$(6,355) million** (compared to $(1,561) million in FY 2024), driven by higher cloud computing, facilities-related costs, and employee expenses.\n*   **FY 2024:** Decreased by $2,412 million to **$(1,561) million** (compared to $(3,973) million in FY 2023).\n\n**Segment Adjusted EBITDA:**\n*   **Q1 2026:** Decreased by $497 million to **$(609) million** (compared to $(112) million in Q1 2025).\n*   **FY 2025:** Decreased by $1,584 million to **$(1,237) million** (compared to $347 million in FY 2024).\n*   **FY 2024:** Decreased by $875 million to **$347 million** (compared to $1,222 million in FY 2023).\n\n---\n\n### 2. AI Segment Cost Breakdown\nThe AI segment\'s expenses are categorized into Cost of Revenue, Research & Development (R&D), Selling, General & Administrative (SG&A), and Restructuring Charges.\n\n**Cost of Revenue**\nIncludes infrastructure costs, revenue share, payment processor fees, creator payments, intangible asset amortization, and allocated labor/overhead.\n*   **Q1 2026:** Increased by **$5 million**.\n*   **FY 2025:** Increased heavily, driven by **$491 million** in higher infrastructure and cloud computing costs (tied to subscriber growth), **$90 million** in employee compensation, **$45 million** in revenue share/creator fees, and **$28 million** in payment processor fees.\n*   *Infrastructure Costs specifically include:* Data center facility leases, hosting, support, maintenance, energy, bandwidth, server/networking equipment depreciation, public cloud hosting, and employee compensation.\n\n**Research and Development (R&D)**\nMainly relates to training the Grok frontier model, developing/testing next-gen AI products, and data center costs. Includes cloud computing, employee compensation, power generation, and depreciation of data center assets (processors, networking).\n*   **Q1 2026:** Increased by **$1,471 million**, driven by GPU hardware depreciation and cloud computing/data center infrastructure expansion.\n*   **FY 2025:** Increased by **$3,888 million** (totaling $5,064 million, up from $1,176 million in 2024), driven by accelerated deployment of compute for Grok, GPU depreciation, and cloud computing costs.\n\n**Selling, General, and Administrative (SG&A)**\nConsists of employee compensation (sales, marketing, finance, legal, IT, HR), professional services (consulting, content moderation, third-party legal/accounting), and unallocated facilities/overhead costs. \n*   *Note:* SG&A is expected to increase in absolute dollars but decrease as a percentage of revenue over time. It may also increase due to a compute agreement with Cursor.\n\n**Restructuring Charges**\n*   Stem from the acquisition of Twitter in October 2022 by X Holdings.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Compute and Infrastructure Costs for Grok\nThe company is making massive, capital-intensive investments in terrestrial and orbital AI compute to train Grok (including the next-generation Grok 5 model) and achieve AGI. \n\n**Data Center Infrastructure (COLOSSUS & COLOSSUS II)**\n*   **Scale & Speed:** The COLOSSUS facilities collectively provide approximately **1.0 gigawatt** of compute power, with COLOSSUS II adding an additional 400MW. The company brought the first COLOSSUS cluster online in 122 days (repurposing an existing factory) and COLOSSUS II in just **91 days**, vastly outpacing the industry benchmark of ~2 years for a 100MW greenfield data center.\n*   **Cost Efficiency:** Construction costs for COLOSSUS II are considerably lower than industry benchmarks on a per-megawatt basis, utilizing a brownfield retrofit strategy.\n*   **Hardware & Networking:** Facilities deploy leading-edge GPUs (such as **GB200s and GB300s**) to maximize training throughput. They utilize advanced direct-to-chip liquid cooling to support higher rack densities and high-speed networking.\n*   **Vertical Integration (Terafab):** To alleviate chip shortages and reduce costs, the company is partnering with Tesla on the "Terafab" initiative to build a manufacturing facility capable of producing 1 terawatt per year of compute hardware.\n\n**Power and Energy Costs**\n*   **Behind-the-Meter Generation:** COLOSSUS II is capable of operating entirely via a self-built, behind-the-meter **gigawatt-scale natural gas power plant**.\n*   **Battery Storage:** Data centers are integrated with the world’s largest **Megapack** deployment for reliability and operating performance.\n*   **Grid Strategy:** The company purchases grid power when available but relies on self-generated power and Megapacks when grid power is curtailed. They also pledge to cover all new power delivery infrastructure upgrade costs so expenses are not passed to ordinary households.\n*   *Financial Impact:* Power generation and energy costs are explicitly listed as major components of both R&D expenses and Cost of Revenue infrastructure costs.\n\n**External Compute Partnerships**\n*   **Cursor:** The company has a compute agreement with Cursor (coding/software development), which is expected to drive up both R&D and SG&A expenses.\n*   **Anthropic:** The company is monetizing unused compute capacity through cloud compute services agreements with Anthropic, though balancing internal Grok training vs. external monetization creates operational complexity and requires substantial capital allocation.',
