 **~4.4M X Premium/Premium+ subscribers**\\n- **Pricing tiers**: $30/month (high-income countries), $8/month (upper-middle/lower-middle-income), ~$12 weighted average globally\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. What the Disclosure **Permits** an Analyst to Conclude About Grok Monetization\\n\\n1. **Grok is a meaningful growth driver**: The combined \\"X and Grok subscription revenue\\" increased by $365M in FY2025 and $177M in Q1 2026. The MD&A explicitly attributes these increases to both X and Grok subscriptions, confirming Grok is contributing incrementally.\\n\\n2. **Subscriber scale is known**: ~1.9M paid Grok subscribers as of March 31, 2026, across three tiers (SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, SuperGrok Lite).\\n\\n3. **Pricing architecture is disclosed**: The $30/$8 tiered pricing and ~$12 weighted average allow an analyst to model a theoretical revenue range. At $12/month average × 1.9M subscribers, annualized Grok consumer subscription revenue would be approximately **$274M** — though this is an analyst inference, not a disclosed figure.\\n\\n4. **API access revenue is immaterial relative to subscriptions**: By residual calculation (total AI Solutions & Infrastructure YoY increase minus disclosed subscription and data licensing increases), API access contributed approximately **~$12M** of incremental revenue in FY2025, **~$7M** in FY2024, and **~$2M** in Q1 2026 — suggesting API monetization is nascent.\\n\\n5. **Grok is deeply unprofitable at the segment level**: The AI segment reported a $(6,355)M operating loss in FY2025 (vs. $(1,561)M in FY2024), driven by $3,888M in increased R&D spend (primarily GPU depreciation and cloud computing for Grok training) and $491M in higher infrastructure costs. Segment Adjusted EBITDA deteriorated from $347M in FY2024 to $(1,237)M in FY2025.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 5. What the Disclosure Does **NOT** Permit an Analyst to Conclude\\n\\n| Analytical Question | Why It Cannot Be Answered |\\n|---|---|\\n| **What is Grok\'s standalone revenue?** | Grok subscriptions are bundled with X subscriptions; no separate figure is provided. |\\n| **What is Grok\'s ARPU?** | Without standalone Grok revenue, average revenue per user cannot be calculated from disclosed data. |\\n| **What is Grok\'s unit economics or contribution margin?** | No cost allocation between Grok and X is disclosed; infrastructure and R&D costs are reported at the segment level. |\\n| **What is Grok Enterprise/Business revenue?** | Enterprise products (Grok Business, Grok Enterprise, xAI Gov) have no revenue disclosure whatsoever. |\\n| **What is Grok API revenue?** | API access is not separately quantified; only a residual can be inferred. |\\n| **Is Grok accretive or dilutive to segment margins?** | Without revenue or cost attribution, margin impact is indeterminate. |\\n| **What is the Grok subscriber growth trajectory?** | Only a single snapshot (1.9M as of March 31, 2026) is provided; no historical subscriber counts for Grok are disclosed. |\\n| **What is the churn rate or retention for Grok subscribers?** | Not disclosed. |\\n| **What portion of the $760B TAM estimate is realistic?** | The TAM is a forward-looking, management-constructed estimate based on the $12 weighted average across 5.5B people — it is aspirational and not grounded in disclosed conversion or penetration data. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary Assessment\\n\\nThe filing\'s disclosure framework provides **two levels of granularity** for the AI segment (Advertising vs. AI Solutions & Infrastructure) and supplements this with **narrative YoY change attribution** for subscriptions and data licensing within the latter bucket. However, **Grok-specific revenue is never isolated** — it is commingled with X subscriptions in all financial disclosures. This permits an analyst to confirm that Grok is a growth contributor and to estimate a rough revenue range using disclosed subscriber counts and pricing, but it **does not permit** rigorous standalone modeling of Grok\'s revenue, profitability, unit economics, or enterprise traction. An analyst seeking to value Grok as a discrete business would need to rely heavily on inference and external data sources beyond this filing.\\n\\n---\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (Filed May 20, 2026)\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## AI Segment Revenue Sub-Component Disclosure Analysis (FY2025)\n\n### 1. Revenue Disaggregation: What Is Disclosed with Granularity\n\nThe AI segment\'s $3,201M of FY2025 revenue is disaggregated into **only two tabular line items**:\n\n| Sub-Component | FY2025 Revenue | FY2024 Revenue | FY2023 Revenue |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Advertising** | $1,844M | $1,728M | $2,323M |\n| **AI Solutions & Infrastructure** | $1,357M | $892M | $638M |\n| **Total AI Segment** | **$3,201M** | **$2,620M** | **$2,961M** |\n\nThese are the **only** sub-components with explicit, absolute-dollar revenue granularity in the filing\'s tabular disclosures.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Sub-Components Described Narratively but NOT Broken Out as Separate Line Items\n\nWithin the "AI Solutions & Infrastructure" bucket ($1,357M in FY2025), the filing\'s revenue recognition notes and MD&A describe **three constituent revenue streams**, none of which receive standalone dollar amounts:\n\n| Sub-Component | Tabular Line Item? | Absolute Dollar Amount? | YoY Change Disclosed? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **X & Grok Subscriptions** (bundled) | No | No | Yes: +$365M (FY25), +$177M (Q1\'26) |\n| **Data Licensing** | No | No | Yes: +$88M (FY25), +$12M (Q1\'26) |\n| **API Access to Grok Models** | No | No | No — residual only (~$12M implied in FY25) |\n\nAdditionally, the filing references **Grok Business**, **Grok Enterprise**, and **xAI Gov** as enterprise product offerings, but provides **zero revenue figures** (absolute or incremental) for any of them. These are embedded within the aggregate AI Solutions & Infrastructure line.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Non-Financial Operational Metrics Disclosed\n\nThe filing provides subscriber counts (as of March 31, 2026) that partially compensate for the lack of revenue granularity:\n\n- **~6.3M total active paid subscribers**, of which:\n  - **~1.9M Grok subscribers** (SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, SuperGrok Lite)\n  - **~4.4M X Premium/Premium+ subscribers**\n- **Pricing tiers**: $30/month (high-income countries), $8/month (upper-middle/lower-middle-income), ~$12 weighted average globally\n\n---\n\n### 4. What the Disclosure **Permits** an Analyst to Conclude About Grok Monetization\n\n1. **Grok is a meaningful growth driver**: The combined "X and Grok subscription revenue" increased by $365M in FY2025 and $177M in Q1 2026. The MD&A explicitly attributes these increases to both X and Grok subscriptions, confirming Grok is contributing incrementally.\n\n2. **Subscriber scale is known**: ~1.9M paid Grok subscribers as of March 31, 2026, across three tiers (SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, SuperGrok Lite).\n\n3. **Pricing architecture is disclosed**: The $30/$8 tiered pricing and ~$12 weighted average allow an analyst to model a theoretical revenue range. At $12/month average × 1.9M subscribers, annualized Grok consumer subscription revenue would be approximately **$274M** — though this is an analyst inference, not a disclosed figure.\n\n4. **API access revenue is immaterial relative to subscriptions**: By residual calculation (total AI Solutions & Infrastructure YoY increase minus disclosed subscription and data licensing increases), API access contributed approximately **~$12M** of incremental revenue in FY2025, **~$7M** in FY2024, and **~$2M** in Q1 2026 — suggesting API monetization is nascent.\n\n5. **Grok is deeply unprofitable at the segment level**: The AI segment reported a $(6,355)M operating loss in FY2025 (vs. $(1,561)M in FY2024), driven by $3,888M in increased R&D spend (primarily GPU depreciation and cloud computing for Grok training) and $491M in higher infrastructure costs. Segment Adjusted EBITDA deteriorated from $347M in FY2024 to $(1,237)M in FY2025.\n\n---\n\n### 5. What the Disclosure Does **NOT** Permit an Analyst to Conclude\n\n| Analytical Question | Why It Cannot Be Answered |\n|---|---|\n| **What is Grok\'s standalone revenue?** | Grok subscriptions are bundled with X subscriptions; no separate figure is provided. |\n| **What is Grok\'s ARPU?** | Without standalone Grok revenue, average revenue per user cannot be calculated from disclosed data. |\n| **What is Grok\'s unit economics or contribution margin?** | No cost allocation between Grok and X is disclosed; infrastructure and R&D costs are reported at the segment level. |\n| **What is Grok Enterprise/Business revenue?** | Enterprise products (Grok Business, Grok Enterprise, xAI Gov) have no revenue disclosure whatsoever. |\n| **What is Grok API revenue?** | API access is not separately quantified; only a residual can be inferred. |\n| **Is Grok accretive or dilutive to segment margins?** | Without revenue or cost attribution, margin impact is indeterminate. |\n| **What is the Grok subscriber growth trajectory?** | Only a single snapshot (1.9M as of March 31, 2026) is provided; no historical subscriber counts for Grok are disclosed. |\n| **What is the churn rate or retention for Grok subscribers?** | Not disclosed. |\n| **What portion of the $760B TAM estimate is realistic?** | The TAM is a forward-looking, management-constructed estimate based on the $12 weighted average across 5.5B people — it is aspirational and not grounded in disclosed conversion or penetration data. |\n\n---\n\n### Summary Assessment\n\nThe filing\'s disclosure framework provides **two levels of granularity** for the AI segment (Advertising vs. AI Solutions & Infrastructure) and supplements this with **narrative YoY change attribution** for subscriptions and data licensing within the latter bucket. However, **Grok-specific revenue is never isolated** — it is commingled with X subscriptions in all financial disclosures. This permits an analyst to confirm that Grok is a growth contributor and to estimate a rough revenue range using disclosed subscriber counts and pricing, but it **does not permit** rigorous standalone modeling of Grok\'s revenue, profitability, unit economics, or enterprise traction. An analyst seeking to value Grok as a discrete business would need to rely heavily on inference and external data sources beyond this filing.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (Filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
